<section class="content" id="goals">
    <p class="heading-1 container">Inspiration</p>
    <div class="flex-grid container">
        <div class="fg--cell content--text center">
            <p>The idea of social robots isn't new. We were inspired by 'Project EMAR', a robotics project run by professors at the University of Washington to create a robot that can collect survey data <em>in context</em> from users. We were inspired by the idea of robots integrating into society, but the <em>biggest obstacle</em> that we noticed was that people interacting with EMAR had <em>expectations</em> of how to interact with it before their first interaction - likely because of its humanoid form.</p>

            <p>Other studies in Human-Robot interaction also suggest that accounting for <em>simple social aspects</em> in the design of robots improves our interactions with them. Robots that are capable of displaying social cues and nonverbal behaviors during collaborative tasks attribute to improved task performance, higher recall accuracy, error prevention and faster task-completion times.</p>

            <p>It was clear from our research that people had social expectations from interactive robots. If robots are to become a part of our everyday lives, it isn't enough if they help us physically. They need to provide <em>mental and emotional assistance</em> as well. This thought helped us derive our research question...</p>
        </div>

        <div class="fg--cell--custom">
